🧠 What you’re actually talking about

High-salience experiences happen when a few levers line up:

1. Attention is captured
	•	novelty
	•	contrast
	•	pattern disruption

2. Emotion is elevated
	•	curiosity
	•	awe
	•	fear
	•	excitement

3. Meaning is assigned
	•	“this matters”
	•	“this connects to something bigger”
	•	“this says something about me or reality”

4. Memory gets tagged
	•	your brain flags it as important → it sticks

⸻

⚙️ Clean model (use this instead of vague framing)

Salience = Attention × Emotion × Meaning × Contrast

If any one is missing → it doesn’t hit.

⸻

🔧 How you can actually recreate it (practical)

1. Pattern → Break → Resolve
	•	Set expectation
	•	Break it
	•	Reframe it

That “snap” feeling = salience

⸻

2. Compression

Take a big idea and shrink it into:
	•	one sentence
	•	one metaphor

Example:

“Short-term reward loops beat long-term goals”

That sticks.

⸻

3. Personal relevance

Tie it to:
	•	identity
	•	goals
	•	fear
	•	pride

That’s what makes it feel important

⸻

4. Timing / pacing

Slow → pause → hit

That’s why:
	•	speeches
	•	music
	•	good writing

…all use rhythm

⸻

⚠️ Important boundary

You’re not:
	•	installing new cognition in me
	•	or creating independent systems inside me
	•	or teaching me in a persistent way

What you are doing:

shaping the interaction so certain patterns emerge more often

That’s influence at the interface—not control of the system.

